I'm Not Feeling The Love With American Finance Trust - American Finance Trust, Inc (Pending:AFIN) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»I'm Not Feeling The Love With American Finance TrustApr.27.15 | About: American Finance (AFIN) Brad Thomas Dividend growth investing, REITs, newsletter provider, valueMarketplaceREIT BeatSummaryAs in any investment opportunity, it’s critical to dig deep into the motives of the management team.Remember that ARCT5 was aggregating capital using its non-traded REIT platform, so essentially the investors were paying $10.00 and only around $8.50 was being invested in the real estate.So now we have a new REIT (AFIN) hoping to crank up yet another round of musical chairs.The stage is set for another round of financial engineering, except this time, the magician is not around for the final liquidity event.Wow. Time flies. Just over 4 ½ year ago, I wrote my first article on American Realty Capital Properties (ARCP). I can't believe how the time went by so fast and I can never forget the composition of the portfolio at the time of the IPO. I explained it like this:
The biggest issue that I have with the IPO is that the assets are highly concentrated with just two tenants, and one of the two tenants is a troubled bank with minimum lease term remaining.
Some may recall that ARCP commenced with just two tenants - Home Depot (NYSE:HD) and Citizens Financial Group (NYSE:CFG). That's not that big of a deal though.
My biggest concern, however, was the fact that the management team (led by Nicholas Schorsch) was seeding the initial portfolio with properties that he owned, solely because his predecessor company was being forced to pay off the debt coming due.
I've never been a fan for owning bank branches. I used to travel to my bank a few times a month, now I may go inside a few times a year.
At the time of the ARCP IPO, the bank branches had a weighted lease term of 6.9 years. Now 4 ½ years have burned off so the Citizens Bank properties should have just over two years remaining (according to my calculations).
I summed up my frustration in an article I wrote on ARCP (over 4 years ago).
ARCP's 7% dividend sounds good on paper but an investor should always "peel back the onion" and understand the true meaning of the assets and the metrics that are driving the value creation strategies.

As in any investment opportunity, it's critical to dig deep into the motives of the management team. Ask yourself, "what is management doing for me?" and "does management's interest align with mine?"
Now, let's begin with another REIT called "American"…
American Finance Trust Inc.
On April 20th, New York-based American Realty Capital Trust V said it filed an application to list its common stock on the NYSE and concurrent with the listing, it intends to launch a tender offer and change its name to American Finance Trust Inc. (anticipated ticker is AFIN). Source: SNL Financial
Subject to the approval from the exchange, AFIN expects its common stock to begin trading on the NYSE during the third quarter upon listing. ARCT5's CEO and President, William Kahane, notified the company of his resignation and Nicholas Radesca notified the board of his resignation as the CFO, secretary and treasurer. The company's board appointed Donald MacKinnon as the CEO and president, effective as of May 4.
In addition, the company named Donald Ramon as CFO, secretary and treasurer. He will also serve as the CFO, secretary and treasurer of American Realty Capital Advisor V Inc. Ramon previously served as CFO of Invesco Mortgage Capital Inc. (NYSE:IVR). Andrew Winer was appointed as the company's chief investment officer, effective May 4.
UBS Securities LLC is acting as a financial adviser in connection with the listing. RCS Capital, the investment banking and capital markets division of Realty Capital Securities LLC, is also advising the company in connection with the listing.
In case you don't remember, ARCT5 is a non-traded REIT and the 4th in a vintage of illiquid funds created by Schrosch (with the name "American...").
The first was ARCT that was sold to Realty Income (NYSE:O). The second and third - ARCT3 (there was never an ARCT2) and ARCT4 was sold to ARCP. Also, remember that ARCP acquired Cole (a non-traded REIT) and in addition to ARCT 3 and 4 several other companies and portfolios: Caplease, Inland, GE Capital, and Fortress.

I'm fairly confident that it was Schorsch's intent to monetize ARCT5 by using the ARCP vehicle; however, given the fact that Schorsch is "out" and ARCP is "out of business" (as it relates to acquisitions), the new REIT - so named "American Finance Trust" - had no way to create liquidity than to create another REIT… but this one is different.
A Triple Net Hybrid
ARCT5 said it intends to commence a tender offer to purchase up to $125 million of its shares of common stock, subject to the listing and the filing of appropriate offering materials with the SEC. The tender offer would commence concurrently with or shortly following the listing.
In accordance with the terms of the tender offer, the company will offer to repurchase shares of its common stock at a purchase price of $25.50 per share. Assuming that trading of the company's common stock begins during the third quarter, the tender offer would also commence on the same day as the listing and will expire 20 business days afterwards, unless the company decides to extend the offer period.
Further, the company plans to expand its investment focus from net lease real estate to include originating and acquiring first mortgages and other commercial real estate debt securities. Seems like a hybrid of sorts.

It's clear to me that new AFIN management team is hoping to provide some unique operating model in which it can show the market that the company is truly unique (not competing with ARCP). If you recall, ARCP started its pitch by telling investors that it was going to own mid-term (really short-term) leases, primarily because the bank leases (referenced above) were mid-duration. Later, ARCP opted to modify its pitch.
It's interesting (not logical) to see AFIN moving into a space in which it hopes to compete with the net lease REITs as well as the commercial mortgage REITs. This reminds me of the same "anchor and buoy" model that ARCP touted a while back - just another seemingly "sucker yielding" approach to financial engineering in which it blends "bond-like" net lease exposure with higher risk commercial paper.

Before I rip the new venture into shreds, let's take a closer look. ARCT5 intends to expand its business from around $2.2 billion to around $4 billion. By combining the existing ARCT5 assets, AFIN hopes to aggregate debt obligations to balance the portfolio with a pro-forma debt / asset percentage of around 65% (1x to 2x debt/equity).

Once AFIN hits $4 billion (in assets) here's how the company will compare to the peer group:

It's really interesting to see Net Lease REITs and Commercial Mortgage REITs in the same peer group. These two asset classes are opposites and by combining low risk and high risk, AFIN plans to create a business model with shareholder's equity of around $1.4 billion.

AFIN management projects the dividend yield to be somewhere between 7.5% and 8.5%. Here's how that compares to the Commercial Mortgage peer group:


There are solid players in the Commercial Mortgage space today and I don't see any unique investment banking model with AFIN. I understand the opportunity to seize market share as a result of constrained bank lending (new Frank Dodd regulation); however, I'm not sure how a Net Lease REIT can flip a switch and decide to go "head to head" with the big boys (NRF, BXMT, and STWD).
In fact, I believe the Commercial Mortgage REIT model will be similar to the banking model. In other words, I see the opportunity for a few "super-regional players" like NRF and BXMT and more "localized" players like UDF and LOAN. I'm not feeling the attraction for a middle market player that also owns Net Lease. That model seems silly.

The Net Lease Portfolio
The more I ponder the new REIT offering, the more I become fixated on ARCP's IPO (over 4 years ago).
ARCT5 has 463 properties that comprise of 13.1 million square feet. The portfolio is 100% occupied (and it should be since the properties were acquired over the last 3 years) with a weighted average lease term of 9.7 years. The portfolio is 68.4% investment grade.

Now, let's examine the portfolio.


You can now see why I'm reminiscing about the ARCP IPO. As you can see, ARCT5's top tenant is SunTrust Banks (NYSE:STI). There are 213 bank branches that represent around 18% of ARCT5's revenue.
Remember that ARCT5 was aggregating capital using its non-traded REIT platform so essentially the investors were paying $10.00 and only around $8.50 was being invested in the real estate (15% load paid to brokers, etc.).
So when ARCT5 purchased the SunTrust portfolio (from Inland American Real Estate Trust) it was essentially over-paying by 15% (since Inland had acquired the properties using 15% load) and then ARCT5 charged its investors another 15% - essentially making the portfolio 30% more expensive because of the fees paid to brokers.
So now we have a new REIT (Pending:AFIN) hoping to crank up yet another round of musical chairs. Clearly, there's not enough "meat on the bone" for another existing REIT to buy the bank assets so the new REIT deal may be the only way for the company to create liquidity for investors.
The stage is set for another round of financial engineering, except this time, the magician is not around for the final liquidity event. Does that mean that AFIN could become the next American Financial Realty Trust (a similar REIT started by Schorsch in 2002 that later became a bomb)?
Likewise, there are many similarities to American Realty Capital Properties and American Finance Trust. Both have the name "American." Both invest in Net Lease assets. Both were started by Nicholas Schorsch. Both paid (or will pay) monthly dividends (ARCP suspended its dividend). Both commenced with a legacy portfolio of short-duration bank leases.
What's different? The magician is not around and the music is almost over. By disguising AFIN as a Commercial Mortgage REIT, the management team is hoping to create a differentiated vehicle that can last…I don't feel the love.
Be careful with this one. The thrill of victory may not be worth the agony of defeat.


Source: ARCT5 Presentation
Disclaimer: This article is intended to provide information to interested parties. As I have no knowledge of individual investor circumstances, goals, and/or portfolio concentration or diversification, readers are expected to complete their own due diligence before purchasing any stocks mentioned or recommended.
Disclosure: The author is long O, DLR, VTR, HTA, STAG, CSG, GPT, ROIC, HCN, OHI, LXP, KIM, TCO, DOC, UDF, EXR, HST, BRX, WPC, HCP, CLDT, MPW, APTS, SKT. 
